text: Coffee is not only a delicious beverage
in Ethiopia it is an essential component
of Ethiopian culture and society an
Ethiopian coffee ceremony begins with
green coffee beans that are roasted
right in front of your nostrils
it only takes moments until the beans
begin to produce an intoxicating
fragrance when the beans are smoking in
the pan the host offers all drinkers a
chance to inhale the fumes pouring from
the roasting coffee beans it's an
opportunity to fully ingest their
delicious aroma and to heighten your
anticipation of the coffee after the
beans are fully roasted the hosts
grounds the beans traditionally using a
mortar and pestle and then adds the
powder to a special Ethiopian clay
coffee pot as the coffee slowly brews
frankincense SAP is burned on hot coals
to produce yet another aromatic incense
that adds to a already heavenly smells
it's easy to fall into a coffee days
dreaming about the coffee and drooling
for your first sip luckily an Ethiopian
coffee ceremony is served with a bowl of
fresh popcorn now I'm not sure exactly
how the tradition first began but I
think the popcorn is served to keep you
from drooling as you anticipate the
ambrosial coffee that's being prepared
brewing Ethiopian coffee takes time the
pot is heated to a boil multiple times
and the host tests it to confirm that
it's of utmost quality before being
poured into the cups many Ethiopians
drink their coffee black with just a
spoon of sugar when the sugar is placed
in the cups you know it's almost time
when the coffee is finally ready the
hosts carefully pours it into small
demitasse glasses stirs in the sugar and
then hands each cup out for the first
round of pure Ethiopian coffee ecstasy
